<p>Seasonal variations are significant, with summer months (June-August) producing 40-45% of annual generation, while winter months contribute 15-20%. However, New York's net metering policies allow homeowners to bank excess summer production as credits for winter consumption, maximizing the value of solar investments. Snow coverage typically affects production for only 10-15 days per year, as panels shed snow quickly due to their smooth surface and heat generation. The state's moderate temperatures actually benefit solar panel efficiency, as panels perform better in cooler conditions compared to extremely hot climates.</p>

