<h2>HVAC Systems in New York</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>New York's climate presents unique HVAC challenges, with heating loads significantly exceeding cooling loads in most regions. The state experiences approximately 5,000-7,000 heating degree days annually compared to only 500-1,200 cooling degree days, making efficient heating systems the primary concern for most homeowners. Winter temperatures regularly drop below freezing for 3-5 months, while summer temperatures typically range from 70-85¬∞F with moderate humidity levels.</p>

<p>For cooling systems, SEER ratings of 16-18 are recommended to balance efficiency with cost-effectiveness, though higher ratings may be justified in downstate regions with greater cooling demands. Heating systems should prioritize cold-weather performance, making cold-climate heat pumps with HSPF ratings of 10+ ideal for many applications. Traditional heating options like natural gas furnaces (90%+ AFUE) or oil systems remain viable in areas with established fuel infrastructure.</p>

<p>Humidity control is important during summer months, particularly in coastal areas, making properly sized systems with good dehumidification capabilities essential. Zoning systems are popular in larger New York homes due to varying sun exposure and occupancy patterns. Air quality considerations, including pollen and urban pollutants, make high-quality filtration systems valuable additions to any HVAC upgrade.</p>

